\begin_layout Subsection
Convergence Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jackson_eigenvalues_2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 it was proved that for traditional choices of polynomial bases, the eigenvalues
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{-1}V^{i}$
\end_inset

 are all 0 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that in the conservative, homogeneous case (
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{\boldsymbol{B}}=\boldsymbol{S}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

), owing to the Banach Fixed Point Theorem, existence and uniqueness of
 a solution are established, and convergence to this solution is guaranteed.
 As noted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dumbser_very_2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, in the linear case it is implied that the iterative procedure converges
 after at most 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

 iterations.
 A proof of this result for the Montecinos-Balsara polynomial basis class
 is now provided here.
 For the theory in linear algebra required for this section, please consult
 a standard textbook on the subject, such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nering_linear_1970"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take the definitions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:inner product matrices"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:compound matrices"

\end_inset

.
 Consider that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U^{-1}V^{k}=E^{-1}M^{\tau}\otimes I^{k-1}\otimes D\otimes I^{3-k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(U^{-1}V^{k}\right)^{m}=\left(E^{-1}M^{\tau}\right)^{m}\otimes\left(I^{k-1}\right)^{m}\otimes D^{m}\otimes\left(I^{3-k}\right)^{m}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is nilpotent (
\begin_inset Formula $X^{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

) if and only if all its eigenvalues are 0.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{-1}V^{k}$
\end_inset

 is nilpotent if 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{m}=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P_{N}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p=a_{j}\psi_{j}$
\end_inset

 for some unique coefficient vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, taking inner products with 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \psi_{i},\psi_{j}\right\rangle a_{j}=\left\langle \psi_{i},p\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,...,N$
\end_inset

.
 This produces the following result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p=a_{j}\psi_{j}\Leftrightarrow\boldsymbol{a}=\left(M^{χ}\right)^{-1}\boldsymbol{x},\;x_{i}=\left\langle \psi_{i},p\right\rangle \label{eq:gramCoeffs-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}\in\mathbb{R}^{N+1}$
\end_inset

, define:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p=a_{0}\psi_{0}+\ldots+a_{N}\psi_{N}\in P_{N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(M^{χ,1}\boldsymbol{a}\right)_{i}=\left\langle \psi_{i},\psi_{0}^{'}\right\rangle a_{0}+\ldots+\left\langle \psi_{i},\psi_{N}^{'}\right\rangle a_{N}=\left\langle \psi_{i},p^{'}\right\rangle 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:gramCoeffs-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\left(M^{χ}\right)^{-1}M^{χ,1}\boldsymbol{a}\right)_{i}\psi_{i}=\left(D\boldsymbol{a}\right)_{i}\psi_{i}=p'
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By induction:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(D^{m}\boldsymbol{a}\right)_{i}\psi_{i}=p^{\left(m\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for any 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P_{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{N+1}\boldsymbol{a}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}$
\end_inset

 was chosen arbitrarily, 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{N+1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 No specific choice has been made for 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and thus the result holds in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, in the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{\boldsymbol{B}}=\boldsymbol{S}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

, existence and uniqueness of a solution are established, and convergence
 to this solution is guaranteed for the iterative solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DGit"

\end_inset

 in the Discontinuous Galerkin case, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:CGit"

\end_inset

 in the Continuous Galerkin case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Operator Splitting Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The material in this section is published in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jackson_fast_2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DensityEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MomentumEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DistortionEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ThermalEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EnergyEquation"

\end_inset

 can be written in the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{\nabla}\cdot\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q}=\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "toro_reimann_2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, a viable way to solve inhomogeneous systems of PDEs is to employ an operator
 splitting.
 That is, the following subsystems are solved:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{\nabla}\cdot\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q} & =\boldsymbol{0}\label{eq:HomogeneousSubsystem}\\
\frac{d\boldsymbol{Q}}{dt} & =\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\label{eq:ODESubsystem}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The advantage of this approach is that specialized solvers can be employed
 to compute the results of the different subsystems.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\delta t},S^{\delta t}$
\end_inset

 be the operators that take data 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}\left(x,t+\delta t\right)$
\end_inset

 under systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HomogeneousSubsystem"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ODESubsystem"

\end_inset

 respectively.
 A second-order scheme (in time) for solving the full set of PDEs over time
 step 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\Delta t\right]$
\end_inset

 is obtained by calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q_{\Delta t}}$
\end_inset

 using a Strang splitting:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{\Delta t}}=S^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}H^{\Delta t}S^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}\boldsymbol{Q_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the scheme proposed here, the homogeneous subsystem will be solved using
 a WENO reconstruction of the data, followed by a finite volume update,
 and the temporal ODEs will be solved with appropriate ODE solvers.
 This new scheme will be referred to here as 
\shape italic
the Split-WENO method
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\rho}{dt}=0$
\end_inset

 over the ODE time step, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 entails solving the following systems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{dA}{dt} & =\frac{-3}{\tau_{1}}\left|A\right|^{\frac{5}{3}}A\dev\left(G\right)\label{eq:DistortionODE}\\
\frac{d\boldsymbol{J}}{dt} & =-\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\frac{T\rho_{0}}{T_{0}\rho}\boldsymbol{J}\label{eq:ThermalODE}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These systems can be solved concurrently with a stiff ODE solver.
 The Jacobians of these two systems to be used in an ODE solver are given
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Jacobian-of-Distortion-ODEs"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Jacobian-of-Thermal-Impulse-ODEs"

\end_inset

.
 However, these systems can also be solved separately, using the analytical
 results presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:The-Thermal-Impulse-ODEs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:The-Distortion-ODEs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, under specific assumptions.
 The second-order Strang splitting is then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{\Delta t}}=D^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}T^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}H^{\Delta t}T^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}D^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}\boldsymbol{Q_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{\delta t},T^{\delta t}$
\end_inset

 are the operators solving the distortion and thermal impulse ODEs respectively,
 over time step 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

.
 This allows us to bypass the relatively computationally costly process
 of solving these systems numerically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Homogeneous System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A WENO reconstruction of the cell-averaged data is performed at the start
 of the time step (as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:The-WENO-Reconstruction"

\end_inset

).
 Focusing on a single cell 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w^{n}}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=\boldsymbol{w^{n}}_{p}\Psi_{p}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{p}$
\end_inset

 is a tensor product of basis functions in each of the spatial dimensions.
 The flux in 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is approximated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\approx\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{w}_{p}\right)\Psi_{p}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w}_{p}$
\end_inset

 are stepped forwards half a time step using the update formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}-\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}}{\Delta t/2}+\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\right)\cdot\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}\right)\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)\right)=\boldsymbol{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}=\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}-\frac{\Delta t}{2\Delta x}\left(\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\right)\cdot\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}\right)\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)\right)\right)\label{eq:WENO half step}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}$
\end_inset

 is the node corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 This evolution to the middle of the time step is similar to that used in
 the second-order MUSCL and SLIC schemes (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "toro_reimann_2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) and, as with those schemes, it is integral to giving the method presented
 here its second-order accuracy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integrating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HomogeneousSubsystem"

\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n+1}}=\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}}-\Delta t_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}+\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{V}\int_{C}\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}\\
\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}} & =\frac{1}{V}\int_{C}\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}\\
\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}} & =\frac{1}{V}\varoint_{\partial C}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\left(\boldsymbol{s},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right),\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\left(\boldsymbol{s},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)\right)d\boldsymbol{s}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q^{-},Q^{+}}$
\end_inset

 are the interior and exterior extrapolated states at the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HomogeneousSubsystem"

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q}=\boldsymbol{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{M}=\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F}}{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}+\boldsymbol{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 be the normal to the boundary at point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\in\partial C$
\end_inset

.
 For the GPR model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}=\boldsymbol{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{s}\right)\right)\cdot\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonalizable matrix with decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}=\hat{R}\hat{\Lambda}\hat{R}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 are the right eigenvectors and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues.
 Define also 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{F}}=\boldsymbol{F}\cdot\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}=\boldsymbol{B}\cdot\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Using these definitions, the interface terms arising in the FV formula
 have the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}},\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{F}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\right)+\boldsymbol{\hat{F}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)+\tilde{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)+\tilde{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{M}$
\end_inset

 is chosen to either correspond to a Rusanov/Lax-Friedrichs flux (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "toro_reimann_2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{M}=\max\left(\max\left|\hat{\Lambda}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\right)\right|,\max\left|\hat{\Lambda}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right|\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or a simplified Osher–Solomon flux (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dumbser_simple_2011,dumbser_universal_2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{M}=\int_{0}^{1}\left|\hat{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right)\right|dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\hat{M}\right|=\hat{R}\left|\hat{\Lambda}\right|\hat{R}^{-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}$
\end_inset

 takes the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{B}=\int_{0}^{1}\hat{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right)dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was found that the Osher-Solomon flux would often produce slightly less
 diffusive results, but that it was more computationally expensive, and
 also had a greater tendency to introduce numerical artefacts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}},\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}$
\end_inset

 are calculated using an 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

-point Gauss-Legendre quadrature, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Thermal Impulse ODEs
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-Thermal-Impulse-ODEs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the EOS for the GPR model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EnergyDefinition"

\end_inset

 and denoting by 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}^{\left(A\right)},E_{2}^{\left(J\right)}$
\end_inset

 the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{J}$
\end_inset

 respectively, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
T & =\frac{E_{1}}{c_{v}}\\
 & =\frac{E-E_{2}^{\left(A\right)}\left(\rho,s,A\right)-E_{3}\left(\boldsymbol{v}\right)}{c_{v}}-\frac{1}{c_{v}}E_{2}^{\left(J\right)}\left(\boldsymbol{J}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =c_{1}-c_{2}\left\Vert \boldsymbol{J}\right\Vert ^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c_{1} & =\frac{E-E_{2}^{\left(A\right)}\left(A\right)-E_{3}\left(\boldsymbol{v}\right)}{c_{v}}\\
c_{2} & =\frac{c_{t}^{2}}{2c_{v}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Over the time period of the ODE 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ThermalODE"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}>0$
\end_inset

 are constant.
 We have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dJ_{i}}{dt}=-\left(\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\frac{\rho_{0}}{T_{0}\rho}\right)J_{i}\left(c_{1}-c_{2}\left\Vert \boldsymbol{J}\right\Vert ^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(J_{i}^{2}\right)=J_{i}^{2}\left(-a+b\left(J_{1}^{2}+J_{2}^{2}+J_{3}^{2}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a & =\frac{2\rho_{0}}{\tau_{2}T_{0}\rho c_{v}}\left(E-E_{2}^{\left(A\right)}\left(A\right)-E_{3}\left(\boldsymbol{v}\right)\right)\\
b & =\frac{\rho_{0}c_{t}^{2}}{\tau_{2}T_{0}\rho c_{v}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that this is a generalized Lotka-Volterra system in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ J_{1}^{2},J_{2}^{2},J_{3}^{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 It has the following analytical solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{J}\left(t\right)=\boldsymbol{J}\left(0\right)\sqrt{\frac{1}{e^{at}-\frac{b}{a}\left(e^{at}-1\right)\left\Vert \boldsymbol{J}\left(0\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Distortion ODEs
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-Distortion-ODEs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{0}=\frac{3}{\tau_{1}}\left(\frac{\rho}{\rho_{0}}\right)^{\frac{5}{3}}>0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 have singular value decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $U\Sigma V^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G=\left(U\Sigma V^{T}\right)^{T}U\Sigma V^{T}=V\Sigma^{2}V^{T}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tr\left(G\right)=\tr\left(V\Sigma^{2}V^{T}\right)=\tr\left(\Sigma^{2}V^{T}V\right)=\tr\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{dA}{dt} & =-k_{0}U\Sigma V^{T}\left(V\Sigma^{2}V^{T}-\frac{\tr\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)}{3}I\right)\\
 & =-k_{0}U\Sigma\left(\Sigma^{2}-\frac{\tr\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)}{3}\right)V^{T}\nonumber \\
 & =-k_{0}U\Sigma\dev\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)V^{T}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a common result (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "giles_extended_2008"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d\Sigma=U^{T}dAV
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\Sigma}{dt}=-k_{0}\Sigma\dev\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using a fast 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 SVD algorithm (such as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mcadams_computing_2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V,\Sigma$
\end_inset

 can be obtained, after which the following procedure is applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, giving 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(t\right)=U\Sigma\left(t\right)V^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote the singular values of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2},a_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Sigma\dev\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
a_{1}\left(a_{1}^{2}-\frac{a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+a_{3}^{2}}{3}\right) & 0 & 0\\
0 & a_{1}\left(a_{1}^{2}-\frac{a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+a_{3}^{2}}{3}\right) & 0\\
0 & 0 & a_{1}\left(a_{1}^{2}-\frac{a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+a_{3}^{2}}{3}\right)
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=\frac{a_{i}^{2}}{\det\left(A\right)^{\frac{2}{3}}}=\frac{a_{i}^{2}}{\left(\frac{\rho}{\rho_{0}}\right)^{\frac{2}{3}}}$
\end_inset

 we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dx_{i}}{d\tau}=-3x_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\label{eq:StretchODESystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\frac{2}{\tau_{1}}\left(\frac{\rho}{\rho_{0}}\right)^{\frac{7}{3}}t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 is the arithmetic mean of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This ODE system travels along the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi=\left\{ x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}>0,x_{1}x_{2}x_{3}=1\right\} $
\end_inset

 to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This surface is symmetrical in the planes 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=x_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 As such, given that the system is autonomous, the paths of evolution of
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 cannot cross the intersections of these planes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, any non-strict inequality of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\geq x_{j}\geq x_{k}$
\end_inset

 is maintained for the whole history of the system.
 By considering 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:StretchODESystem"

\end_inset

 it is clear that in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is monotone decreasing, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k}$
\end_inset

 is monotone increasing, and the time derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 may switch sign.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
\frac{dx_{i}}{d\tau}=-x_{i}\left(2x_{i}-x_{j}-x_{k}\right)=-x_{i}\left(2x_{i}-x_{j}-\frac{1}{x_{i}x_{j}}\right)\\
\frac{dx_{j}}{d\tau}=-x_{j}\left(2x_{j}-x_{k}-x_{i}\right)=-x_{j}\left(2x_{j}-x_{i}-\frac{1}{x_{i}x_{j}}\right)
\end{array}\right.\label{eq:2odes}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, an ODE solver can be used on these two equations to effectively solve
 the ODEs for all 9 components of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Note that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dx_{j}}{dx_{i}}=\frac{x_{j}}{x_{i}}\frac{2x_{j}-x_{i}-\frac{1}{x_{i}x_{j}}}{2x_{i}-x_{j}-\frac{1}{x_{i}x_{j}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This has solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{j}=\frac{c+\sqrt{c^{2}+4\left(1-c\right)x_{i}^{3}}}{2x_{i}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c=-\frac{x_{i,0}\left(x_{i,0}x_{j,0}^{2}-1\right)}{x_{i,0}-x_{j,0}}\in\left(-\infty,0\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i,0}=x_{j,0}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=x_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all time.
 Thus, the ODE system for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has been reduced to a single ODE, as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}\left(x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be inserted into the RHS of the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dx_{i}}{d\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 However, it is less computationally expensive to evolve the system presented
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2odes"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Bounds on the Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If any of the relations in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\geq x_{j}\geq x_{k}$
\end_inset

 are in fact equalities, equality is maintained throughout the history of
