\begin_layout Subsubsection
Viscous Shock
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This test is designed to demonstrate that the numerical methods used are
 also able to cope with fast flows.
 First demonstrated by Becker 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "becker_impact_1929"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the Navier-Stokes equations have an analytic solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{r}=0.75$
\end_inset

 (see Johnson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "johnson_analytical_2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a full analysis).
 As noted by Dumbser et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dumbser_high_2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, if the wave has nondimensionalised upstream velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{v}=1$
\end_inset

 and Mach number 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{c}$
\end_inset

, then its nondimensionalised downstream velocity is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a=\frac{1+\frac{\gamma-1}{2}M_{c}^{2}}{\frac{\gamma+1}{2}M_{c}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wave's velocity profile 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{v}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is given by the roots of the following equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1-\bar{v}}{\left(\bar{v}-a\right)^{a}} & =c_{1}\exp\left(-c_{2}x\right)\\
c_{1} & =\left(\frac{1-a}{2}\right)^{1-a}\\
c_{2} & =\frac{3}{4}R_{e}\frac{M_{c}^{2}-1}{\gamma M_{c}^{2}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}$
\end_inset

 are constants that affect the position of the center of the wave, and its
 stretch factor, respectively.
 Following the analysis of Morduchow and Libby 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "morduchow_complete_1949"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the nondimensional pressure and density profiles are given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{p}=\frac{1}{\bar{v}}\left(1+\frac{\gamma-1}{2}M_{c}^{2}\left(1-\bar{v}^{2}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\rho}=\frac{1}{\bar{v}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain an unsteady shock traveling into a region at rest, a constant
 velocity field 
\begin_inset Formula $v=M_{c}c_{0}$
\end_inset

 is imposed on the traveling wave solution presented here (where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the adiabatic sound speed).
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0},\rho_{0}$
\end_inset

 are the downstream (reference) values for pressure and density:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
v & =Mc_{0}\left(1-\bar{v}\right)\\
p & =p_{0}\bar{p}\\
\rho & =\rho_{0}\bar{\rho}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These functions are used as initial conditions, along with 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\sqrt[3]{\bar{\rho}}I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{J}=\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The downstream density and pressure are taken to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}=\frac{1}{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}=1$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{c}=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{e}=100$
\end_inset

.
 The material parameters are taken to be: 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=1.4$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\infty}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{v}=2.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}=5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}=5$
\end_inset

, 
